SIMPLE: insecurity
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Insecurity
<hw>In`se*cu"ri*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Insecurities</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Pref. <ets>in-</ets>
not + <ets>security</ets> : cf. LL. <ets>insecuritas</ets>, F.
<ets>insecurite</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The condition or quality
of being insecure; lack of safety; danger; hazard; <as>as, the
<ex>insecurity</ex> of a building liable to fire; <ex>insecurity</ex> of
a debt.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The state of feeling insecure; uncertainty; lack of
confidence.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With what <qex>insecurity</qex> of truth we ascribe effects . . .
unto arbitrary calculations.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T. Browne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A time of <qex>insecurity</qex>, when interests of all sorts
become objects of speculation.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Insecution</ent>⟦br⟧
